From 3aadb1cd527a88dc13661ec9df4d4a1f00570945 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: vllm-shim <vllm-shim@local>
Date: Thu, 1 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 6/6] fix(quark): bypass moe_sorting for MoRI EP MXFP4,
 pre-mask topk_ids in Python

Under MoRI EP the dispatcher hands a fixed-capacity buffer with GLOBAL
topk_ids and undefined padding rows beyond num_local_tokens[0]. The
earlier patch routed the block-align step through AITER's moe_sorting
(first moe_sorting_fwd, later moe_sorting_opus_fwd) because those do
the global->local expert remap that SGLang's Triton align kernels do
not. Both AITER variants turn out to emit sorted_token_ids in an
encoded chunked-dispatch layout (upper bits encode the dispatch chunk
index, e.g. 0x01000000+i for chunk 1) that the CK MXFP4 GEMM was
designed to decode. The Triton MXFP4 GEMM treats sorted_token_ids as
plain flat (token * top_k + slot) indices and masks via
``offs_token < num_valid_tokens``, so it sees the encoded upper bits
as out-of-range and skips every write. The visible effect was all-zero
output on every DP whose chunk index was nonzero, and wrong-expert
garbage on the one DP whose chunk happened to land in the valid range.
Diagnosed via the SORT-DUMP scaffolding (now removed; it served its
purpose).

Bypass moe_sorting entirely. The remap that AITER's sort embedded in
its sorted_token_ids encoding is decomposable into two ops we can do
on device before the align kernel runs:

  1. Build a global->local id table from expert_mask: cumsum(0)-1 at
     each local position, sentinel ``num_experts`` (out of the per-
     expert bucket range) at each non-local position.
  2. Gather to remap topk_ids into local-id space and mask
     dispatch-buffer padding rows (row >= num_local_tokens[0]) to the
     same sentinel via one broadcasted comparison.

Then run SGLang's existing _moe_align_block_size kernels at the LOCAL
expert count. The align kernel's per-expert counter drops sentinel
values on the floor (they match no bucket), and its sorted_token_ids
padding fill (= num_valid_tokens) is the exact value the Triton GEMM's
mask catches. No special-casing in the Triton call path is needed.

Side effects of the rewrite, all dropped because the underlying race
they patched around no longer exists:

  - stage2_topk_weights sentinel scatter (was needed when AITER's CK
    sort wrote num_local_tokens[0] into sort padding, contaminating a
    valid flat index). SGLang's align fills with num_valid_tokens
    instead, which the kernel mask handles natively.
  - sentinel-flat skip in the pure-torch reference (was mirroring the
    above scatter).
  - SORT-DUMP diagnostic and _log_sort_dump helper (specific to
    debugging AITER's encoded sorted_token_ids).

Workspace adds three EP-only buffers: local_hash (align_experts int32),
local_topk_ids (M * top_k int32), row_arange (M * 1 int32, pre-filled
in eager warmup). The non-EP path is untouched.

Found debugging Kimi K2.6 MXFP4 on 8x MI300X; not upstreamed.
