-    # to this rank carry weights, but topk_ids still holds global expert ids
-    # and expert_mask (global length, local experts = 1) marks them. In that
-    # mode the block-align step must run through moe_sorting_fwd, which does
-    # the global->local expert remap and emits -1 expert ids for the
-    # dispatch buffer's padding rows (the Triton GEMM writes zeros for those).
-    # The SGLang Triton align kernels cannot: they index a per-expert counter
-    # by raw topk_ids values and walk off the end on the padding rows. Non-EP
-    # (num_local_tokens is None) keeps the align-kernel path unchanged.
+    # to this rank carry weights, but topk_ids still holds GLOBAL expert ids
+    # and rows beyond num_local_tokens[0] are pre-allocated capacity slack
+    # with undefined topk_ids/topk_weights. Both AITER moe_sorting variants
+    # (moe_sorting_fwd / moe_sorting_opus_fwd) emit sorted_token_ids in an
+    # encoded chunked-dispatch layout (upper bits encode the dispatch chunk
+    # index) that the CK MXFP4 GEMM was designed to decode. The Triton MXFP4
+    # GEMM treats sorted_token_ids as plain flat (token * top_k + slot)
+    # indices and masks via ``offs_token < num_valid_tokens``; it sees the
+    # encoded upper bits as out-of-range and skips every write, producing
+    # all-zero output on every DP whose chunk index is nonzero and
+    # wrong-expert garbage on the one DP whose chunk happens to land in the
+    # valid range. (Diagnosed via the [SORT-DUMP] dump in earlier patches.)
+    #
+    # Bypass moe_sorting entirely: do the global->local remap and the
+    # padding-row mask in Python on device, then run SGLang's existing
+    # _moe_align_block_size kernels at the LOCAL expert count. Non-local
